Michael Norrish wrote:
>
>The easiest fix is not to allow TOs to be vacated at all.  This is
>what I think is best.  I'm not quite sure what the difference betwen
>TOs and POs is such that one should be able to be vacated and the
>other not, but I feel it exists. 

I agree, and I'll take a stab at stating the difference.  TOs
are, in one sense (and purely an extra-legal one), satisfied
immediately.  Yes, they do impose a requirement on the recordkeepor,
but in fact when Bob posts a transfer to me, as long as the
transfer is valid (Bob has enough of the given currency), I
have those currencies available for immediate use.  I can
in fact spend those currencies before Bob's TO is de jure satisfied
by being recorded by the recordkeepor.

If we thus think of TOs as being satisfied immediately, then
not allowing them to be vacated falls in line with the "satisfied
Orders cannot be vacated, or (same thing) vacation of a satisfied
Order has no effect."

POs, of course, are not immediately satisfied, so can be vacated
(with effect).

Chuck


