BUS: PROTO: Order Fix, Final

Swann wrote:

<snip>

(I don't have any real problems with the first part here.)

>      Any Private Order that is of a type not explicitly permitted by
>      the Rules, or is not pursuant to an agreement between the Player
>      issuing it and the entity to which the Order is directed, or is
>      not affecting such an Order, is presumptively invalid until proven 
>      otherwise by CFJ.

I'm afraid I do not see this as a fix at all, as I'll elucidate below.


>      In order to be proven valid by CFJ, the Rules must;

>       i) Permit the Player who executed the Order in question to 
>           execute such an Order.

Since the Rules permit all Players to issue Private Orders, this is no
restriction at all.

>       ii) Require or permit the execution of the Order in the 
>           circumstances which existed at the time it was executed.

I'm still waiting to see what circumstances would *prevent* the execution of a
Private Order.  So far, only orders that seek to compel a Player to break the
Rules would be invalid.

>      iii) Not explicitly render it invalid.

Same thing.  The Rules to not explicitly render any Order invalid, unless it
would force a Player to break the Rules.

<snip>

>     An Order shall be for an improper purpose if it does not conform to 
>     the purpose of such an Order as broadly defined in the Rules.  The 
>     following shall be the minimum considerations for determining the 
>     proper purpose for each class of Order;

>       i) Private Orders shall not be for a proper purpose unless they 
>          are directly relevant to the personal business of the Player 
>          issuing them, or to the business of entities of which that
>          Player is an Executor, or are persuant to a binding agreement
>          betwen the Player issuing the Order and the entity being so
>          Ordered.

What is the personal business of the Player issuing them?  Certainly gaining
wealth and Kudos, getting your proposals moved up in the queue and getting them
passed are all direcly relevant.  I don't think this restriction works to
prevent people from ordering transfers, votes, or other actions that we would
normally consider improper.

Actually, I fail to see the need for any Private Orders that are not explicitly
defined by the Rules.  If you want to enforce private agreements, add penalty
clauses to the agreement or define standard penalties for broken agreements,
both of which can be enforced by the courts.

-- Crito


